SIMPLE: puffin
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Puffin
<hw>Puf"fin</hw> <pr>(p⟦ucr⟧f"f⟦icr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to
<ets>puff</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An arctic
sea bird <spn>Fratercula arctica</spn>) allied to the auks, and having a
short, thick, swollen beak, whence the name; -- called also
<altname>bottle nose</altname>, <altname>cockandy</altname>,
<altname>coulterneb</altname>, <altname>marrot</altname>,
<altname>mormon</altname>, <altname>pope</altname>, and <altname>sea
parrot</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The name is also applied to other related species, as
the horned puffin (<spn>Fratercula corniculata</spn>), the tufted puffin
(<spn>Lunda cirrhata</spn>), and the razorbill.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Manx puffin</b></col>, <cd>the Manx shearwater. See under
<er>Manx</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The puffball.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A sort of apple.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Rider's Dict. (1640).</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puffiness</ent>⟦br⟧
